Is Listening to a Book Just as Good as Reading It?

Do you listen to audiobooks? What are the benefits, in your opinion, of listening instead of reading? Are there advantages to reading that cannot be gained by listening? Which method do you prefer? Why?

---

In my opinion,

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: For example, driving can easily be done while listening to an audiobook.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: But I prefer to listen to audiobooks when I'm doing mindless tasks, like washing the dishes or folding laundry.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Reading actively involves deciphering the words as you read, while listening requires active attention and forces you to imagine the words and images in your head instead of

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: I find that I retain much more from a book I have read, rather than listened to it, though the former takes much more time than the latter

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: I have to pay attention to the narrator, so I can't skim, look up references or think about a main idea while I drive.
